My goal with this was to create stl viewer but push it to extreme so that I can see how it starts breaking in terms of computation time and mesh viewer and how can I optimize it?
I used LLM to do boilerplate and some common code generation and I focused on volume computation and viewer logic.
flow of my projects is it will accept stl via frontend send it to my exe and it will compute area and volume.

Q. why 3js
    For visualization. Larger goal of project is user should be able to click on triangle in browser.
    Right now I'm able to generate mesh and show it in browser but most heavy lifting is done by 3js
    I want to do that manually to learn I have computed all edges and able to show them but it breaks beyond 500k.

Q. what is stl? what exactly does it store?
  It stores triangles only. 3 vertices and 1 normal. No topology. No units. No connectivity nothing very basic.
    {
      Q. Why normal?
      A => Historical. Old machines did not have computer power to compute it again. Today's machine can.
      Q. From 3 points you can define a plane but that plane can have two normals in opposite direction. How do you find then inside and outside of surface?
      A => Winding Order Decides the Direction. 
            If vertices are ordered:
            Counter-clockwise (CCW) → normal points outward (by convention)
            Clockwise (CW) → normal points inward
            So orientation is not random — it depends on ordering.
    }

What problems you faced this projects? How you solved them
  1. Reading stl files. STL files is always 50 bytes for each triangle but creating it's struct makes it 52 bytes due to padding.
      So if you make struct like this
      struct Triangle {
        float normal[3];   // 12
        float v1[3];       // 12
        float v2[3];       // 12
        float v3[3];       // 12
        uint16_t attr;     // 2
      };
      and fill this struct using
        file.read(reinterpret_cast<char*>(&t), sizeof(Triangle));
      then it will read 52 bytes into file instead of 50.
  2. Triangle not visible.
      Camera issue. We need to set camera at corner of bounding box
  3. Parsing is happening two times. First manually at backend and again at fronend by 3js. Avoid it at fronend. We directly parse it at backend and pass triangles only.
  4. Excessive vector reallocations. Used vector reserve instead of push_back
  5. If you store map<edge, face> at starts to explode beyond 10M there are others solutions like flat_map and absil from google. I have not used them yet but because of this project I understood limitations of STL
  {
    4. We add id to each triangle ourselves so when clicked on frontend it gives that id. Id's are set by us.
    5. For computing normals and storing:
        For our cases when id' are 1,2,3 we can use vector but in production we might need to use Hashmap.
        And at 10M and above hashmap starts breaking. also trade off between std::array and std::vector. For write once read heavy.
  }

{
  Q. Types of STL ASCII vs Binary STL?
  ASCII STL: Human-readable text format.
  Binary STL: Much more compact and faster. (Most common)
    [80 bytes]   Header
    [4 bytes]    Number of triangles (uint32)
    [50 bytes]   Triangle 1
    [50 bytes]   Triangle 2

    So ideal parser design:
      1. Read 80 bytes header
      2. Read uint32 count
      3. Reserve vector capacity
      4. Loop read 50 bytes per triangle
      For large files (millions of triangles):
      1. Use memory mapping (mmap)
      2. Or bulk read into buffer
}

Q. How do you compute surface area of a triangle mesh? Why does the cross product magnitude give triangle area?
A => For triangle with points A, B, C:
      e1 = B - A
      e2 = C - A
      area = 0.5 * |e1 x e2|
      Why it works:

      |e1 x e2| gives area of the parallelogram formed by the two edges.
      Triangle is half of that parallelogram.

Q. How did you compute volume
A = >
so we first find bounding box for shape
we find equidistant points inside that box on all 3 sides
so now we know volume of box and if we can find how many percent of points are actually inside shape we can use that percent to get volume of shape (approx)
so it now become problem of finding if given point is inside shape or not
now for given point how we find if it's inside shape or not is by drawing arrow with point as origin if intersect at odd point then ouside otherwise inside
but that mean I need to check every point with every triangle
that is 1M vs 1M that's too much
so what we do is we divide original bounding box into 8 small box and 8 small box and then in this way we can see if ray is intersecting any of that bounding only then we can use traingles from that box so this can work as tree with 8 nodes every time and we trave tree based on checking intersecting
and once we find how many triangles it intersect we can decide if point is inside or outside and based on percentage of how many points are inside to toal points we get volume

GPT of above answer:
To estimate the volume of an STL mesh, I used a Monte Carlo–style numerical method.
First, I compute the axis-aligned bounding box of the mesh. That gives me a known volume region that fully contains the shape.
Then I sample a large number of evenly distributed points inside that bounding box. Since I know the box volume, if I can determine what fraction of those points lie inside the mesh, I can approximate the mesh volume as:
volume ≈ (inside_points / total_points) × bounding_box_volume.
So the core problem becomes: how do we test whether a point lies inside the mesh?
For that, I use ray casting. From each sample point, I shoot a ray in a fixed direction and count how many times it intersects the mesh surface. If the number of intersections is odd, the point is inside; if even, it’s outside.
A naive implementation would check every ray against every triangle, which becomes too slow for large meshes. So I built a spatial acceleration structure — specifically an octree — by recursively subdividing the bounding box into smaller boxes. Each node stores only the triangles that intersect that region.
During ray testing, I traverse only the relevant octree nodes, so instead of testing against all triangles, I test only a small subset. This reduces the complexity significantly and makes the method scalable up to around 1M triangles.
Finally, based on the ratio of inside points, I compute the approximate volume.

